passages.text: F3Q25 Review: Solid PGMand Tands Help Navigate Plethora of Macro Challenges and Push Estimate Risks Worries Beyond FY25

In our view, HPQ will push the wall of investor worries relative to a potential slowdown in the PC market (following a pull- forward led by tariff worries) as well as concerns relative to delivering to robust Print margins in the face of higher competition, with its latest F3Q results managing to deliver on both fronts as well as keep its full- year outlook intact following the lowered expectations last quarter. The company expects the refresh momentum to continue with Enterprise customers led by Windows 11 refresh and also led by adoption of AIPCs, reaching \(25\%\) of mix for HPQ already, across Consumers and Enterprises supporting a large and increasing installed base of AI PCs that will enable HPQ to leverage and monetize further innovations on this front. Additionally, the company delivered to the promised margin expansion q/q in the PS segment through a combination of pricing and acceleration of supply chain footprint shift to support all US volumes from non- China locations, and the company expects the same drivers to support another q/q improvement in F4Q25. For Print, the outlook for the underlying industry remains largely similar for a low single digit decline in both FY25 and FY26 but the company is continuing to pull levers to mitigate tariff and competitive headwinds to deliver margins solidly in the \(16\% - 19\%\) range in F3Q (17.3%) and guide to sequential improvement to the high- end of the range in F4Q. The resilience of the results and the outlook aside though, concerns are likely to remain in relation to potential changes in the tariff landscape in the coming months, with the company currently leveraging the Sec 232- related exemption for PCs to supply the US market from a diversified footprint across Mexico, Asia- ex China, EMEA, and LatAm, which, while unlikely to impact its FY25 (October- end) results, will be an overhang for the FY26 outlook in addition to continuing concerns in relation to digestion in the PC market and higher competitive pressures in the office print market given limited recovery. Despite a largely unchanged earnings outlook we are raising our Dec- 26 price target to \(\) 30\(vs.\) \ \(27\) to reflect the lower estimate risk to FY25.

F3Q25 (Jul- end) Results: EPS roughly in line with expectations on robust revenue and in- line operating margins. Revenue tracked to \(\) 13.9\(bn vs. JPME of\) \ \(13.9\) bn and consensus of \(\) 13.7\(bn, with Personal Systems (PS) revenue of\) \ \(9.9\) bn tracked in line with JPME of \(\) 9.9\(bn but above consensus of\) \ \(9.7\) bn, and Print revenue at \(\) 4.0\(bn, in line with JPME and consensus of\) \ \(4.0\) bn. Despite the robust revenues, operating margins tracked to \(7.1\%\) modestly below JPME and consensus of \(7.2\%\) . PS margins were below JPME but modestly above consensus expectations ( \(5.4\%\) vs. JPME of \(5.6\%\) and consensus of \(5.3\%\) ), led by a mix shift toward higher- value premium offerings including AI PCs as well as pricing, while Print margins tracked below JPM and consensus expectations ( \(17.3\%\) vs. JPME of \(18.5\%\) and consensus of \(19.2\%\) ) but still delivering to the long- term range of \(16\% - 19\%\) . Our Overweight rating on HPQ shares reflects our medium- term view of positioning. We believe HPQ's PS segment is favorably positioned, which is expected to be the primary driver of the recovery. In addition, with gross margins stabilizing following the digestion of inventory in the channel, we expect operating margin upside to stem from revenue leverage off a lean cost structure. We expect the combination of structural margin improvement in the Print segment on account of several initiatives undertaken by the company to offset some of the margin moderation in the coming quarters with easing supply, even though margin moderation is more muted than previously feared on better supply- demand balance.

We are increasing our December 2026 price target to \(\) 30\((vs.\) \ \(27\) prior) based on valuing our FY27 EPS estimate at an \(\sim 8.5x\) target P/E multiple, which is roughly in line with the current multiple and the long- term historical average.
EPS tracked to \(\) 0.75\(vs. JPM e of\) \ \(0.76\) , consensus of \(\) 0.74\(and prior guide of\) \ \(0.68\) - \(\) 0.80\$ .

F4Q25 (Oct- end) Guidance: Revenue and margin guides roughly in line with expectations drive EPS forecast in line with expectations. PS revenue is expected to be in line with prior year seasonality of \(+2\%\) q/q (vs. JPM e of flat q/q and consensus of \(2.4\%\) q/q), driven by the holiday uptick, the Windows 11 refresh, and continued AI PC adoption, while PS margins are expected to be solidly within the \(5\%\) to \(7\%\) range (vs. JPM e and consensus of \(6.2\%\) ), with sequential improvement as cost mitigation measures fully take effect. Print revenue is also expected to track to prior year seasonality of \(+7\%\) q/q (vs. JPM e of \(8.1\%\) and consensus of \(6.2\%\) ), and Print margins are expected to track to the upper end of the long- term target range of \(16\%\) to \(19\%\) (vs. JPM e of \(19.5\%\) and consensus of \(19.0\%\) ). Consequently, EPS is expected to track to a range of \(\) 0.87-\ \(0.97\) (midpoint of \(\) 0.92\(vs. JPM e and consensus of\) \ \(0.91\) ). For the full- year, the company continues to expect FCF to track the range of \(\) 2.6-\ \(3.0\) bn (vs. JPM e of \(\) 2.8\(bn and consensus of\) \ \(2.7\) bn).

2025 and 2026 Market Guidance: PS market to remain robust while Print market to continue to see structural decline. Management outlined that the company expects the PC market to grow mid- single digits in 2H25, driven by the Windows 11 refresh and increased adoption of AI PCs, with these catalysts to continue driving growth into 2026. For the Print market, however, the company anticipates a decline in the low single digits in 2025, with similar levels of decline continuing into 2026.
